Laevinum, Valeri genus] The Va- leria ‘ gens' was one of the most ancient in Rome, and embraced some of the most distinguished families, among others that of Publicola, the earliest member of which mentioned in history is Valerius Publicola, the eolleague of Brutus after the expulsion of the kings. The family of Laevinus was another branch of the same gens, the most conspicuous of whom were P. Valerius Laevinus, who conducted the war against Pyrrhus, and M. Valerius, who in the . second Punic war was governor of Sicily. of the Laevinus in the text we know no- thing but from the text and the Scholiasts Porphyrion and Comm. Cruq., who say that he was a man of most abandoned cha- racter, so bad that even the populace, who were not easily deterred from conferring their honours upon the vicious, could not be prevailed on by admiration of his high ancestry to advance him beyond the quae- storship 3 that is to say, he never held a curule office. ‘ Valeri genus ' is like ‘ au- dax Iapeti genu3‚' C. i. 3. 27 n.
